ChemmineR: introductory session

Mik Black

25 October 2016

This material covers a VERY basic introduction to some of the functionality provided by the ChemmineR package for R.

It borrows (very) heavily from:

  • http://www.bioconductor.org/packages/devel/bioc/vignettes/ChemmineR/inst/doc/ChemmineR.html

R libraries

The main R package used during this session is ChemmineR. You can install this via:

## Source the biocLite.R installation script
source("http://bioconductor.org/biocLite.R") 

## Use biocLite to install the package
biocLite("ChemmineR")

Additional complication(s)

Additional functionality can be added to the ChemmineR package through the OpenBabel C++ library, accessed via the ChemmineOB R package. This provides extra format conversion and local peptide structure viewing capabilities. As described in the manual, ChemmineR will automatically detect whether ChemmineOB is installed. To get OpenBabel installed on my (Mac OS) laptop, I used the v2.3.1 zip file from:

http://openbabel.org/wiki/Category:Installation

and then installed the ChemmineOB package via:

source("http://bioconductor.org/biocLite.R")
biocLite("ChemmineOB")

For comparing compounds, and performing clustering, the fmcsR package is needed:

source("http://bioconductor.org/biocLite.R")
biocLite("fmcsR")

  • Backman, T. W. H., Cao, Y., & Girke, T. (2011). ChemMine tools: an online service for analyzing and clustering small molecules. Nucleic Acids Research, 39(suppl), W486–W491. http://doi.org/10.1093/nar/gkr320

Bioconductor page:

  • https://www.bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/html/ChemmineR.html

The ChemMine website

The ChemMine website provides a collection of tools for working with structure data from small molecules: - drawing structures - similarity searching - clustering

Even cooler, all of this functionality can be accessed from within R via the ChemmineR package.

http://chemmine.ucr.edu/

ChemmineR: Getting started

Load the ChemmineR library:

library(ChemmineR)

and the ChemmineOB package if you have it installed:

library(ChemmineOB)

Some background: data formats

This data can handle molecular structure data is the following formats:

  • SDF
  • smiles

Let’s learn what these formats look like by loading some data.

Importing SDF objects

Import some SDF data from Thomas’s web page (you can ignore the warning about an “incomplete final line”):

sdfset <- read.SDFset("http://faculty.ucr.edu/~tgirke/Documents/R_BioCond/Samples/sdfsample.sdf") 
## Warning in readLines(sdfstr): incomplete final line found on 'http://
## faculty.ucr.edu/~tgirke/Documents/R_BioCond/Samples/sdfsample.sdf'
## Warning in matrix(as.numeric(ctma[, -4]), nrow = length(ct), ncol = Ncol
## - : NAs introduced by coercion
## Warning in read.SDFset("http://faculty.ucr.edu/~tgirke/Documents/R_BioCond/
## Samples/sdfsample.sdf"): 1 invalid SDFs detected. To fix, run: valid <-
## validSDF(sdfset); sdfset <- sdfset[valid]

This means that sdf.visualize( sdfset[1] ) will succeed (as it requires a SDFset object), but sdf.visualize( sdfset[[1]] ) will fail, since sdfset[[1]] is a “SDF”, not a “SDFset”.

What can we do with this information? Let’s try plotting it. This command:

## Opens browser window and plots structure using Chemmine web service 
sdf.visualize( sdfset[1] )

will open the ChemmineR website and display the first structure in a web browser.
It should look like this:

If you have the OpenBabel package installed, the following command will plot the structure in R:

## With the ChemmineOB package loaded (and OpenBabel installed) you can plot locally:
plot(sdfset[1], regenCoords=TRUE, print=FALSE)

You can also plot multiple compounds from a SDFset:

## With the ChemmineOB package loaded (and OpenBabel installed) you can plot locally:
plot(sdfset[1:4], regenCoords=TRUE, print=FALSE)

What about the other (smiles) format? With OpenBabel, we can do format conversion:

smileset <- sdf2smiles(sdfset)

What does this format look like?

## 
## Display the first smiles object
smileset[[1]]
## An instance of "SMI"
## [1] "O=C(NC1CCCC1)CN(c1cc2OCCOc2cc1)C(=O)CCC(=O)Nc1noc(c1)C"

There are also functions for importing (and exporting) smiles data.

What else can we do?

Who wouldn’t want to identify rings?!

ringatoms <- rings(sdfset[1], upper=Inf, type="all", arom=FALSE, inner=FALSE)
## What did we get?
ringatoms
## $ring1
## [1] "N_10" "O_6"  "C_32" "C_31" "C_30"
## 
## $ring2
## [1] "C_12" "C_14" "C_15" "C_13" "C_11"
## 
## $ring3
## [1] "C_23" "O_2"  "C_27" "C_28" "O_3"  "C_25"
## 
## $ring4
## [1] "C_23" "C_21" "C_18" "C_22" "C_26" "C_25"
## 
## $ring5
##  [1] "O_3"  "C_28" "C_27" "O_2"  "C_23" "C_21" "C_18" "C_22" "C_26" "C_25"

And plot them! (rings are highlighted in red).

atomindex <- as.numeric(gsub(".*_", "", unique(unlist(ringatoms))))
atomindex
##  [1] 10  6 32 31 30 12 14 15 13 11 23  2 27 28  3 25 21 18 22 26
plot(sdfset[1], griddim=c(1,1), print=FALSE, colbonds=atomindex)

NB: using the griddim parameter above allows you to specify the layout of the plot (like the mfrow amd mfcol parameters in teh base plot command). If you don’t specify it, teh SDF plotting function will figure it out for you (which is cool), but it also seems to remember it for next time (which isn’t cool if you are plotting a different number of molecules).

You can even plot the atoms if you want…

plot(sdfset[1], print=FALSE, atomnum=TRUE, no_print_atoms="H", colbonds=atomindex)

Similarity searching

The fmcsR package can be use to identify similar substructures between compounds (i.e., “Maximum Common Substructure”: MCS). The following code loads a new SDFset of structures (only three), and looks for MCSs between the first two.

## Load fmcsR package
library(fmcsR)

## Load SDFset
data(fmcstest)
length(fmcstest)
## [1] 3
## Search for MCS (with mismatches)
## au and bu are the upper bonds for atom and bond matches respectively
test <- fmcs(fmcstest[1], fmcstest[2], au=2, bu=1) 

# Plot both query compounds, with MCS in color 
plotMCS(test)

“Atom Pair” (AP) data format

The “atom pair” (AP) representation that can be used for structural similarity searching and clustering.

# Create an AP representation for single compound
ap <- sdf2ap(sdfset[[1]]) 

# Create an AP representation for a set of compounds
apset <- sdf2ap(sdfset)
## Warning in sdf2ap(sdfset): One or more compounds failed to return APs. To identify them, run: 
##   which(sapply(as(apset, "list"), length)==1)
view(apset[1:4])
## $CMP1
## An instance of "AP"
## <<atom pairs>>
## 52614450304 52615497856 52615514112 52616547456 52616554624 ... length: 528 
## 
## $CMP2
## An instance of "AP"
## <<atom pairs>>
## 52614458368 52615498880 52615498881 52616547456 52616554496 ... length: 325 
## 
## $CMP3
## An instance of "AP"
## <<atom pairs>>
## 52614450176 52614450177 52615496704 52615498880 52615498881 ... length: 325 
## 
## $CMP4
## An instance of "AP"
## <<atom pairs>>
## 52614449152 52614458368 52614458369 52614465536 52614465537 ... length: 496

What does this format actually represent?

## Raw format
apset[[1]]
## An instance of "AP"
## <<atom pairs>>
## 52614450304 52615497856 52615514112 52616547456 52616554624 ... length: 528
## First 6 entries (out of 528) in "human readable" format
head(db.explain(apset[1]))
## [1] "C [1 neighbor(s),0 pi electrons]<---1--->C [3 neighbor(s),1 pi electrons]"
## [2] "C [1 neighbor(s),0 pi electrons]<---2--->C [2 neighbor(s),1 pi electrons]"
## [3] "C [1 neighbor(s),0 pi electrons]<---2--->O [2 neighbor(s),0 pi electrons]"
## [4] "C [1 neighbor(s),0 pi electrons]<---3--->C [3 neighbor(s),1 pi electrons]"
## [5] "C [1 neighbor(s),0 pi electrons]<---3--->N [2 neighbor(s),1 pi electrons]"
## [6] "C [1 neighbor(s),0 pi electrons]<---4--->N [2 neighbor(s),0 pi electrons]"
## Reminder - what does this compund look like?
plot(sdfset[1], print=FALSE)

You can use the AP format to calculate the similarity of any pair of molecules:

cmp.similarity(apset[1], apset[2])
## [1] 0.2637037

Similarity searching

Search for compounds in the apset object that are similar to the first compound.

## Search for compounds similar to CMP1
cmp.search(apset, apset[1], type=3, cutoff = 0.3, quiet=TRUE) 
##   index   cid    scores
## 1     1  CMP1 1.0000000
## 2    67 CMP67 0.3117569
## 3    15 CMP15 0.3010753

NB: for some reason the following code was giving me multiple errors when running with knitr, but it should be fine in the console.

## Plot CMP1 and CMP96 (the one most similar to CMP1)
## Note that I am using the SDFset format here
plot(sdfset[c(1,96)], print=FALSE)

## Identify and plot the MCS between CMP1 and CMP96
test <- fmcs(sdfset[1], sdfset[96], au=2, bu=1) 
plotMCS(test)

Clustering

cmp.duplicated(apset, type=1)

plot(sdfset[c("CMP60", "CMP61", "CMP56", "CMP57")], print=FALSE)

The cmp.cluster function placs compounds into “similarity bins”. Compounds are placed in the same bin if their similraity score exceeds a threshold.

clusters <- cmp.cluster(db=apset, cutoff = c(0.7, 0.8, 0.9), quiet = TRUE)
## 
## sorting result...
clusters[1:12,]
##      ids CLSZ_0.7 CLID_0.7 CLSZ_0.8 CLID_0.8 CLSZ_0.9 CLID_0.9

## 49 CMP49        2       48        2       48        2       48
## 54 CMP54        2       54        2       54        2       54
## 55 CMP55        2       54        2       54        2       54
## 56 CMP56        2       56        2       56        2       56

## null device 
##           1

## [1] FALSE FALSE
## What do they look like?
plot(sdfset[c("CMP48", "CMP49")], griddim=c(1,2), print=FALSE)
